comment:
Amber may actually have narcissistic personality disorder and likely be a sociopath. She believes she's better than others and ensures her throne is not taken, for if it is, she tries to lie and cover it up, or goes into a rage. She plays the victim and steals others stories to do so, while blaming and gas-lighting the actual victim in the process. She paints a picture of herself as a hero who's mighty and an invincible force who can do whatever she wants and not get caught. I think she joined the feminist and charity movements not out of kindness, but for her own public image. She wants others to view her as a kind person, like Mother Teresa. She wants to be viewed as a humanitarian, a survivor of something she never experienced, and an image to young girls, when ironically, that's not a woman to look up to. She wants fans to build an empire to back her up when her victim who came to her seductive trap tries to tell the truth and exploit her for what's she has done and who she actually she is in real life. She wants to appear as the good guy who have been through sexist abuse and she likely uses that victim card to get what she wants, be it support, special treatment, money, or fame. 

However, victim cards can last only so long before they eventually expire and are no longer deemed useful. Looking good and having a humanitarian and kind public image and fan base to back you up even when you are a suspect, also known as using a fake persona or being two-faced, will eventually wear off and people will eventually see that person's true colors. And you can only be a queen for so long before you have to retire, before you die, or before you're overthrown. Gas-lighting can only alter a person's reality for so long before they uncover what reality truly is. And no matter how hard you cover up evidence or lie as well as you can, evidence will be uncovered and truth will be told.

And justice will be served, whether alive or dead. For if you don't get brought don't by justice for your crimes in your lifetime, when you die, your Maker will bring you down by justice and uncover the truth of your past life.

comment: I think she is one if the best examples why #trustallwomen is bad. The concept of #metoo is very important, but even then we can't presume the accused to be guilty. The accusation must be fairly investigated, but the guilt of the accused must be proven before he can be punished. If a person gets accused unfairly and then treated as if guilty it can ruin their lifes to the point where they kill themselves. If however on the other hand a victim gets ignored or even blamed for it it can hurt not only her mental health, but her physical health if she can't get him away from herself, and it can hurt other persons because the abuser gets away with it and abuse them. These are the reasons why balancing this is very hard, and there need to be many discussions on when it is okay for people or institutions to treat someone accused as guilty, and when to only place him under investigation. And we need to be very careful with when to judge them if not by trial. But for AH, there truly only is the deepest layer of hell waiting, as Dante said, around the devil frozen in a block of ice are those who betrayed others, and AH not only betrayed many person, she betrayed the idea of truth and the idea of taking people seriously when they accuse someone else with abuse. And for the court system to deny the appeal on the case of defamation because the judge made a horrible decision is truly corrupt.

comment: May the world realize that one individual does not color an entire movement. Unfortunately, as mentioned here, Ms. Heard's actions have made the proving of other assault charges that much more difficult to prove. Yes, I believe that every report needs to be investigated fully, as this sadly does show us there are the few cases out there where the man is not to blame; but rather than use this as a crutch against #MeToo, we should use it as a reminder that the Victim is often difficult to be heard, and it is the duty of we the people to take time and listen, to coax rather than bully, to provide an environment that is safe for the one who claims to be a victim while thoroughly investigating BEORE casting judgment. Do I blame #MeToo for castigating Johnny Depp in the beginning? ABSOLUTELY NOT!! This movement is established to protect victimized women, and the news portrayed someone in power abusing his position to victimize a woman. These women - like Ms. James - were deceived by one who claimed to be on their side. I just pray the rest of us can learn to step back from the insanity that is Social Media and learn to look at a situation thoroughly before making our judgements one way or another.

comment: I know that a lot of movements like the Black Lives Matter movement or the MeToo movement were made and put into place for reasons that were intended for good reasons and I get that. But than when you see that those who represent those movements doing something or saying something that's totally against those movements. That shows that some of these movements are forever damaged and make it that much harder for real victims to be heard or to speak out. This is sadly proving that the MeToo movement and the feminist movement are indeed hurting because of Amber Heard's actions. I'm not trying to be mean about this, no, I'm just stating that we're all a flawed species, no one is perfect, no movement and no system is perfect. I'm not into politics nor am I into anything involving them but this coming to light is not looking good for the MeToo movement or the feminist movement for those who are real victims. I've known plenty of women and men that are the sweetest people anyone could ever meet and they would never do anything to hurt anyone. But I've come to accept that we are not perfect, no one is. Seeing and hearing this shows that one simple action or one person's actions can hurt more people than we think it can.
